import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists(): return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing: existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]: existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
"34": {
"1": "<p>The Canaan boundary description forms a distinct literary unit within Numbers 34. Ancient Near Eastern boundary documents — border surveys, royal land grants, and vassal treaties — routinely specified the four-directional limits of territories using named landmarks. The Hittite vassal treaties (13th century BCE) and Egyptian administrative papyri both use the same convention: enumerate northern, southern, eastern, and western limits by mountain, river, city, and sea. Israel's boundary is given in the same genre, but its warrant is divine — not royal decree but YHWH's explicit designation.</p>",
"2": "<p>The 'land of Canaan according to its borders' is the specific inheritance promised, not a general region. The Torah's precision here responds to ancient uncertainty about what exactly 'Canaan' meant — the term had political, ethnic, and geographical ambiguities even in the Bronze Age. Ugaritic and Egyptian texts use 'Canaan' variously. Numbers 34 resolves the ambiguity by drawing actual lines, creating a legal title document for the inheritance.</p>",
"3": "<p>The southern boundary begins at the wilderness of Zin along Edom's border, running from the eastern end of the Dead Sea. The Dead Sea's southern shore (<b>yam hamelach</b>, the Salt Sea) was the fixed eastern anchor point for the southern boundary. Ancient maps and administrative documents consistently used major bodies of water as the clearest boundary markers; the Salt Sea was unambiguous.</p>",
"4": "<p>The southern border curves through the Negev highlands — Akrabbim Ascent, Zin, Kadesh-barnea, Hazar-addar, Azmon. These are Bronze Age sites along the traditional southern route connecting Sinai/Egypt to Canaan. Kadesh-barnea in particular was a major oasis with administrative significance — it appears in Egyptian and Mesopotamian documents as a waystation on the major north-south desert route.</p>",
"5": "<p>The boundary turns toward the Mediterranean ('the Great Sea' — <b>hayam hagadol</b>). The Mediterranean was called 'the Upper Sea' in Akkadian administrative texts (as opposed to the Persian Gulf, 'the Lower Sea'). Its use as a western boundary is geographic simplicity at its most elegant — no elaborate description needed for the sea's western edge.</p>",
"6": "<p>The western boundary is the Great Sea alone — the simplest possible delineation. The sea provides an unambiguous natural border that requires no further specification. Unlike the eastern, northern, and southern borders with their named cities and mountains, the western border is one word: the sea. This simplicity reflects the sea's absolute clarity as a boundary in the ancient mind.</p>",
"7": "<p>The northern border runs from the Great Sea to Mount Hor (not the Hor where Aaron died, but a different northern peak). The identification of the northern Mount Hor is debated — Ras Shaqqah (near modern Tripoli, Lebanon) and Jebel Akkar are candidates. The northern boundary extends into what was later Phoenician territory, corresponding to the maximal extent of Davidic and Solomonic influence (1 Kgs 8:65).</p>",
"8": "<p>'Lebo-hamath' (<b>levo chamat</b>) — literally 'the entrance to Hamath' — appears repeatedly in the DtrH as the northern limit of Israel's territory. It marked the boundary between Israelite and Aramean/Phoenician territory throughout the monarchic period. Amos 6:14 threatens that YHWH will oppress Israel 'from Lebo-hamath to the Wadi Arabah' — the traditional northern and southern limits.</p>",
"9": "<p>The northern boundary runs east from Zedad to Ziphron to Hazar-enan. These sites are not all positively identified archaeologically, though some scholars connect them to known sites in modern Syria and Lebanon. The precision serves ancient administrative purposes — boundary disputes required named landmarks, and the text's specificity suggests a genuine survey tradition underlying the literary description.</p>",
"10": "<p>The eastern boundary runs south from Hazar-enan to Shepham — beginning the descent along the eastern side of the promised land. The eastern border must distinguish Cisjordan (west of the Jordan) from Transjordan — the two-and-a-half tribes already settled east of the Jordan (ch32) are explicitly excluded from this survey (v13-15).</p>",
"11": "<p>From Shepham the border descends to Riblah east of Ain, then to the slopes of the Sea of Kinnereth (Sea of Galilee). Riblah on the Orontes later becomes infamous in 2 Kings 23:33 and 25:6 as the site where Pharaoh Necho and Nebuchadnezzar executed Israelite kings. The geography of promise and the geography of punishment share the same coordinates.</p>",
"12": "<p>The boundary follows the Jordan river south to the Dead Sea. The Jordan as eastern border is both geographic reality and symbolic divide — from Joshua's crossing (Josh 3) through the end of the monarchy, the Jordan marked the eastern edge of the inheritance. The Jordan appears in the geography of salvation history: the crossing echoes the Red Sea, and John's baptism happens at a Jordan crossing point.</p>",
"13": "<p>The nine and a half tribes receiving west-of-Jordan allotments are named as the recipients of this survey. The land distribution 'by lot' (<b>goral</b>) reflects the ANE practice of using lot-casting for fair distribution of disputed or ambiguous resources — land, duties, and offices were regularly assigned by lot in Mesopotamian and Egyptian contexts. In Israel, lot-casting acknowledged that the ultimate distribution belonged to YHWH, not human preference.</p>",
"14": "<p>The two-and-a-half tribes (Reuben, Gad, half-Manasseh) who received Transjordanian territory are explicitly excluded from the Cisjordanian boundary survey. Their territory was already delineated in Numbers 32. The separation is administrative, not spiritual — both groups are part of Israel; their inheritance just lies on different sides of the Jordan.</p>",
"15": "<p>'Opposite Jericho, toward the sunrise' (<b>mizrach hashemesh</b>) — the Transjordanian territory is consistently described in relation to Jericho and the Jordan crossing. Jericho, the first conquest target (Josh 6), serves as the reference point for all directional descriptions in this section of Numbers. The geography of Numbers anticipates the narrative of Joshua.</p>",
"16": "<p>The designation of Eleazar and Joshua as land distributors pairs priestly and civil authority. In the ANE, major land grants were typically administered by royal officials with witnesses; Israel's distribution uses the high priest (Eleazar) and the military-civil leader (Joshua). The pairing ensures neither religious nor civil interests dominate the distribution — both serve together.</p>",
"17": "<p>Eleazar (priest) and Joshua (military leader) together will oversee the lot-apportionment. Joshua's role is the continuation of Moses's administrative function — he has been consistently identified as Moses's successor (Num 27:18-23). The combination of priestly authority (Eleazar) and covenantal succession (Joshua = Moses's successor) ensures legitimate distribution of the promise.</p>",
"18": "<p>One leader from each tribe — the <b>nesiim</b> — will oversee the distribution. The same word used for the tribal leaders of the census (ch1) and the dedication offerings (ch7) continues here. The nesiim are the consistent tribal governing class throughout Numbers 1-36, providing administrative continuity from the Sinai encampment to the Canaan entrance.</p>",
"19": "<p>Caleb son of Jephunneh for Judah — the survivor of the spy generation. His presence here is a quiet narrative triumph: the man who gave a minority report from the twelve spies (ch13) and was promised a personal inheritance (ch14:24) is now appointed to oversee Judah's land distribution. Faithfulness outlasts its opposition.</p>",
"20": "<p>Shemuel for Simeon — representing the tribe whose territory will be absorbed into Judah's (Josh 19:1). The administrative process treats Simeon as a full tribal equal even though the fulfillment of the tribal allotment will be different from what Simeon's leader might have expected. The gap between the administrative promise and its historical fulfillment is part of the story of many tribes.</p>",
"21": "<p>Elidad for Benjamin — the tribe that will produce Saul, the first king (1 Sam 9-10). Benjamin's future centrality in early Israelite monarchy is entirely invisible in this appointment list. The boundary survey names Benjamin's representative without any hint of what this tribe will mean to Israel's next three centuries.</p>",
"22": "<p>Bukki for Dan — the tribe that will relocate entirely (Judg 18). The Danite territory in the original allotment (Josh 19:40-48) proved impossible to hold against Philistine pressure; the tribe migrated north and established a new settlement at Laish/Dan. This appointment lists Dan in its original Shephelah context, before the migration that would make 'from Dan to Beersheba' (the north-south idiom) refer to a different location.</p>",
"23": "<p>Hanniel for (western) Manasseh — half-Manasseh west of Jordan received the central highlands. The division of Manasseh across the Jordan created an unusual administrative situation: one tribe with two territorial allotments in different regions, separated by the Jordan. Hanniel represents only the western half; the eastern half's inheritance was already settled (ch32).</p>",
"24": "<p>Kemuel for Ephraim — the dominant central-highland tribe. Ephraim's territory would encompass Shechem, the great central sanctuary site, and the city of Shiloh where the tabernacle would rest (Josh 18:1). The designation of Ephraim's land representative thus anticipates the significance of Ephraim's territory for the entire tribal federation's worship life.</p>",
"25": "<p>Elizaphan for Zebulun — whose Galilean territory would become the region of Jesus's ministry (Matt 4:13-16, fulfilling Isa 9:1-2). The boundary appointees are doing their administrative work without any awareness of the prophetic trajectory of the territories they're receiving. The land they apportion will one day be the land where 'the people who walked in darkness have seen a great light.'</p>",
"26": "<p>Paltiel for Issachar — the Jezreel Valley tribe. The Jezreel Valley was the most fertile agricultural land in Canaan — the breadbasket of the region. The appointment of Issachar's leader to receive this allotment corresponds to Jacob's blessing of Issachar as a 'strong donkey crouching between its saddlebags' who sees that 'the land was pleasant' (Gen 49:14-15).</p>",
"27": "<p>Ahihud for Asher — the tribe whose territory runs along the northern coastal plain (Galilee coast). Asher's land grant includes some of the most commercially significant territory in ancient Canaan — the coastal trading cities and the Jezreel Valley's northwestern approaches. The prophetess Anna (Luke 2:36), who recognized the infant Jesus at the temple, came from Asher.</p>",
"28": "<p>Pedahel for Naphtali — the tribe whose Sea of Galilee territory would frame Jesus's Galilean ministry. Naphtali and Zebulun together are named in Isaiah's 'land of the shadow of death' oracle (Isa 9:1-2). The survey of this land in Numbers 34 is the legal title; Isaiah's prophecy is the eschatological promise; Matthew 4:13-16 is the fulfillment.</p>",
"29": "<p>The list closes with the declaration: 'These are those whom YHWH commanded to apportion the inheritance to the Israelites in the land of Canaan.' The chapter's purpose is complete — a divine mandate, a precise survey, and appointed human administrators. Three elements together constitute legitimate title: divine grant, geographic specification, and named recipients. Numbers 34 provides all three.</p>"
},
"35": {
"1": "<p>The plains of Moab remain the setting — still the threshold moment, still east of the Jordan. The Levitical city provisions are given here, before the crossing, so that the settlement structure is planned before Israel enters. This is characteristic of the priestly legislation in Numbers: the instructions precede the events they govern, ensuring the institutions are conceptually in place before they need to function.</p>",
"2": "<p>The forty-eight Levitical cities represent a distinctive feature of Israelite social organization without close parallel in the ancient Near East. Mesopotamian societies had temple cities and priestly estates concentrated at specific sanctuaries; Israel's system deliberately distributes the priestly-Levitical population throughout every region of the land. This ensures no tribe lacks access to Levitical service, and that the Levites — who have no territorial inheritance — are sustained across the whole nation.</p>",
"3": "<p>The <b>migrash</b> (pastureland) surrounding each Levitical city was standardized: 1,000 cubits from the city wall in every direction (v4), with the measurement zone extending to 2,000 cubits (v5). The standardization is a form of equity — every Levitical city, regardless of which tribe hosts it, has the same surrounding pasture. The consistent measurement prevents wealthy tribes from providing minimal lands and poorer tribes from being overburdened.</p>",
"4": "<p>1,000 cubits of pastureland surrounding the city on each side. The precision reflects the same administrative attention to detail that characterizes the tabernacle dimensions, the offering quantities, and the boundary descriptions. YHWH's provision for his servants is exact, not vague. The Levites know precisely what they are receiving.</p>",
"5": "<p>2,000 cubits measured in each direction from the city itself — placing the city at the center of a square pasture. The geometry is straightforward: the city is the center, the pasture forms a square ring around it. The arrangement makes the Levitical city a self-contained unit wherever it's located within the tribal territory hosting it.</p>",
"6": "<p>Six of the forty-eight cities are designated as cities of refuge — three east of the Jordan and three west. The integration of the refuge cities within the Levitical city system is significant: the same Levites who mediate between YHWH and Israel also mediate between the blood-guilt system and those who shed blood accidentally. The priestly and judicial functions are housed together.</p>",
"7": "<p>Forty-eight cities total, given proportionally from each tribe (v8). The number forty-eight has no obviously symbolic significance but serves practical coverage: roughly four cities per tribe ensures Levitical presence in every region. Archaeological evidence suggests some of the named Levitical cities were historically significant Bronze Age administrative centers before the Israelite settlement.</p>",
"8": "<p>The proportional contribution principle — more cities from larger tribes, fewer from smaller — applies the same equity logic used in the Passover lamb (one per household, with household size governing one or two families sharing) and the sanctuary tax (half-shekel equally from all). The provision is scaled to ability while the distribution ensures full coverage.</p>",
"9": "<p>The cities of refuge (<b>arei miklat</b>) institution assumes a settled society with established kinship networks. The law governing them responds to the real social dynamics of clan-based justice: in the ancient Near East, when someone was killed — even accidentally — the family of the deceased was obligated to pursue the killer. Israel's refuge system channels this legitimate kinship obligation through an adjudicative process rather than leaving it to unregulated pursuit.</p>",
"10": "<p><em>Miklat</em> (refuge/asylum) appears only here and in the parallel passages (Josh 20-21, Deut 4:41-43, 19:1-13). The root may relate to <em>kalat</em> (to contain/receive). The city 'receives' or 'contains' the person seeking asylum — a physical embodiment of legal protection. Many ANE sanctuary sites offered similar asylum; Israel's system systematizes and extends this to purpose-built cities rather than temple precincts.</p>",
"11": "<p>Three cities east and three west of the Jordan ensures geographical accessibility. The Talmudic elaboration (b. Makkot 10a) specifies that roads to cities of refuge had to be kept in good repair and clearly marked. The institution's designers clearly intended it to be practically accessible, not merely theoretically available — the manslayer must be able to reach the city before the blood avenger catches him.</p>",
"12": "<p>The <b>goel haddam</b> (blood redeemer/avenger) is the same word as the <b>goel</b> (kinsman-redeemer) of Ruth and Job. The root <em>ga'al</em> means to act as a close kinsman by fulfilling kinship obligations — redeeming property, marrying a widow, and avenging a killed relative were all <em>goel</em> functions. The system does not abolish the goel's avenger role; it regulates it by interposing the congregation's judgment between the chase and the execution.</p>",
"13": "<p>The congregation (<b>edah</b>) serves as the judicial body. This is Israel's participatory justice — not a professional judiciary but the communal assembly functioning as court. The elders of the city of refuge (Josh 20:4) represent the congregation in practice. The manslayer must be heard; unilateral execution by the blood avenger without adjudication is prohibited.</p>",
"14": "<p>The three east-of-Jordan cities were designated by Moses himself before his death (Deut 4:41-43: Bezer, Ramoth-gilead, Golan). The three west-of-Jordan cities were designated by Joshua (Josh 20:7: Kedesh, Shechem, Hebron-Kiriath-arba). The institution spans the Moses-Joshua transition, implemented by two leaders in sequence — a designed continuity.</p>",
"15": "<p>The cities of refuge are explicitly for the <b>ger</b> (sojourner) and <b>toshav</b> (temporary resident) as well as Israelites. The extension of the protection to non-Israelites is notable: the legal mechanism of the congregation's judgment and the blood-avenger's obligation applied regardless of ethnicity. The land's justice system serves all who live under Israel's covenantal order, not only covenant members.</p>",
"16": "<p>The distinction between murder and manslaughter is determined by circumstances and intent, not merely outcome. An iron instrument used to strike someone suggests deliberate lethal intent — iron weapons were expensive, purpose-built for killing, not everyday agricultural tools. The evidentiary reasoning is from the weapon to the intent.</p>",
"17": "<p>A stone large enough to kill, used to strike someone — circumstantial evidence of murder. The progression through iron (v16), stone (v17), and wood (v18) covers the full range of hand weapons. In each case, the capacity of the weapon to kill is treated as evidence of the killer's intent to kill. Ancient jurisprudence, like modern, infers intent from action and instrumentality.</p>",
"18": "<p>A wooden weapon capable of killing. The categorical completeness (iron, stone, wood) ensures the law cannot be evaded by appealing to the material of the weapon. Whatever the instrument, if it was capable of killing and was used with apparent lethal intent, the law of murder applies. The comprehensive coverage prevents lawyerly parsing of the material categories.</p>",
"19": "<p>The blood avenger shall put the murderer to death — when he meets him, he shall put him to death. The blood avenger operates within a legal framework, not outside it. His action after the congregation has judged and determined guilt is lawful execution, not vigilante violence. The distinction between lawful killing and murder applies to the avenger as well.</p>",
"20": "<p>The intent-revealing circumstances: enmity (<b>sinah</b> — hatred), lying in wait (<b>tzadah</b> — deliberate ambush), or throwing at someone with a purpose to harm. Each of these reveals premeditation — the killing was not accidental but planned or emotionally motivated. Hatred and premeditation are the markers of murder in Israelite law.</p>",
"21": "<p>Or striking out of hostility so that the victim dies — this is murder; the blood avenger may put the murderer to death when he meets him. The 'meeting' language is significant: the avenger may execute the convicted murderer wherever their paths cross, not only in a formal setting. The legal judgment is permanent; the avenger is always authorized to carry it out.</p>",
"22": "<p>The accidental-killing criteria begin with the absence of the murder markers: no enmity, no premeditation, no intention to harm. The verb <b>hedaf</b> (push suddenly/unexpectedly) and the qualifier 'without enmity' distinguish a sudden physical interaction from a calculated assault. Modern law preserves this distinction between manslaughter and murder.</p>",
"23": "<p>Throwing without seeing — the accidental projectile that kills an unintended victim. The circumstantial evidence of accident: no prior relationship of enmity, no deliberate aim, the victim was not even visible. The congregation must weigh these circumstances and apply the distinction. The law trusts communal discernment to evaluate context, not just action.</p>",
"24": "<p>The congregation judges between the manslayer and the blood avenger according to these rules. The congregation is the ultimate arbiter — not the blood avenger's kinship passion, not the manslayer's self-interest, but the community's collective application of YHWH's standards. The institutions of justice exist to channel human conflict through communal deliberation.</p>",
"25": "<p>The congregation's rescue of the manslayer from the blood avenger is a legal act — the congregation physically returns the manslayer to the city of refuge, providing an official escort if needed. The manslayer's residence in the city is not voluntary self-exile but a legally mandated protective custody: he must stay, and the congregation is responsible for his return if he was wrongly pursued.</p>",
"26": "<p>The condition of protection: remaining within the city's limits. If the manslayer leaves before the high priest's death, the blood avenger is legally entitled to kill him. The city's protection is not absolute but conditional on compliance. This condition shapes the manslayer's life: he must remain, even if the city is not his home, even if his family is elsewhere, until the high priest dies.</p>",
"27": "<p>The high priest's death as the release mechanism is the most theologically arresting feature of the system. No other provision releases the manslayer — not the payment of ransom (v31), not the passage of time, not the birth of a new heir. Only the death of the high priest. The high priest's life is tied to the manslayer's confinement; his death brings freedom. The theological implications unfold differently in Numbers 35 than they would after Hebrews 9.</p>",
"28": "<p><em>Chukat mishpat</em> — 'a statutory regulation for justice' — marks this as permanent law rather than situational guidance. The cities of refuge institution is not an emergency measure for the wilderness period; it is the ongoing legal framework for life in the settled land. Joshua 20 implements it; Deuteronomy 19 elaborates it; the institution persists through the monarchic period.</p>",
"29": "<p>The two-witness requirement for capital punishment: no one shall be put to death on the testimony of only one witness. This principle is foundational to Israelite criminal procedure (Deut 17:6, 19:15) and has profound implications. The legal protection it provides is intentionally difficult to overcome — it requires corroboration, making false accusation more difficult and protecting the accused against malicious prosecution.</p>",
"30": "<p>No ransom (<b>kofer</b>) for a murderer's life — the death penalty is mandatory and non-negotiable for convicted murder. This was not universally assumed in the ancient Near East: Babylonian law (Code of Hammurabi) allowed monetary compensation in some homicide cases. Israel's prohibition of ransom in murder cases reflects the absolute weight placed on human life made in God's image (Gen 9:6). Money cannot compensate for a deliberate taking of the image-bearer's life.</p>",
"31": "<p>No ransom to shorten the manslayer's exile — the only exit is the high priest's death. This prohibition prevents the wealthy from buying their way out of the system and the poor from being stuck in it indefinitely while the rich escape. The equalizing principle of the sanctuary is enforced: rich and poor manslayers serve the same term under the same condition.</p>",
"32": "<p>The land itself is a moral entity that can be polluted by unpunished bloodshed. This is not merely a legal principle but a cosmological one: the land has a moral responsiveness to what happens on it. Genesis 4:10 established this — Abel's blood cried out from the ground. Numbers 35:33 generalizes the principle: bloodshed defiles the land, and only blood can atone for blood.</p>",
"33": "<p><em>Kapparah</em> (atonement/covering) for the land — the same word used for the day of atonement (<em>Yom Kippur</em>). The land, like the sanctuary, can accumulate defilement and requires atonement. The judicial execution of the murderer is framed as the land's atonement, not merely the victim's justice. This theological framing elevates the criminal justice system from social management to cosmic maintenance.</p>",
"34": "<p>'You shall not defile the land in which you live, in the midst of which I dwell, for I YHWH dwell in the midst of the Israelites.' The entire legal edifice of the chapter — cities of refuge, two witnesses, no ransom, blood atoning for blood — rests on this foundation: YHWH's presence in the land. Where God dwells, moral order must be maintained. The legal system is not merely practical but theological: it keeps the land fit for the presence of the holy God who has chosen to inhabit it.</p>"
},
"36": {
"1": "<p>The family heads of the Manassite clan of Gilead approach Moses with a legal problem — a case study in how the earlier inheritance ruling for Zelophehad's daughters (ch27:1-11) creates an unintended consequence for tribal land continuity. The petition is respectful and legally precise: they do not contest the prior ruling but identify its systemic implication.</p>",
"2": "<p>They cite YHWH's command to give the land by lot and YHWH's command to give Zelophehad's inheritance to his daughters. Both commands are YHWH's; the problem arises not from anyone's disobedience but from the collision of two legitimate principles — daughters' inheritance rights and tribal land continuity. The text presents this as a genuine legal tension, not a bad-faith challenge.</p>",
"3": "<p>The problem: if the daughters marry men from other tribes, their inherited land follows them into the new tribe. At the jubilee, land returns to its tribe — but the daughters' land, now belonging to another tribe by their marriage, would transfer permanently. The jubilee's function (Lev 25) was to prevent permanent alienation of ancestral land, but marriage creates an exception the jubilee cannot correct.</p>",
"4": "<p>The jubilee year (<b>yovel</b>) — every fifty years, all land reverts to its original tribal allocation, and all debt-slaves are freed (Lev 25). The Zelophehad daughters' case exposes a gap in the jubilee mechanism: it can reverse commercial land sales but not land transferred by inheritance through inter-tribal marriage. The clan leaders identify a genuine loophole in the land-protection system.</p>",
"5": "<p>YHWH vindicates the petition: 'The tribe of the sons of Joseph is right.' The recognition of the complaint's legitimacy is significant — not every legal petition receives divine validation. This one does. The prior ruling favoring daughters' inheritance was also right; both rulings are right, and the resolution must honor both.</p>",
"6": "<p>The resolution: the daughters may marry anyone they choose, but within their father's tribe's clan. <em>Ba-tov be'eineihem tihyenah lenashim</em> — 'let them be wives to whom it seems good in their eyes.' The freedom of choice is preserved — no specific husbands are appointed. The only restriction is tribal endogamy. The narrowest possible constraint that resolves the land-continuity problem without coercing the women into specific marriages.</p>",
"7": "<p>'So that no inheritance of the Israelites shall transfer from tribe to tribe.' The principle stated here becomes permanent law (v8). The land distribution system's integrity requires that tribal boundaries be maintained not just by administrative fiat but by the marriage choices of heiresses. The social and legal systems reinforce each other: the jubilee handles commercial transfers; the marriage rule handles inheritance transfers.</p>",
"8": "<p>The ruling generalizes beyond Zelophehad's daughters: every daughter who possesses an inheritance in any Israelite tribe must marry within her father's tribal clan. The case law becomes precedent. This is standard ancient Near Eastern legal reasoning: a case resolution establishes a rule that applies to all similar cases. The specific case of five named women becomes universal law.</p>",
"9": "<p>'No inheritance shall transfer from one tribe to another' — the principle is absolute and permanent. The Nuzi tablets (15th-14th century BCE) from Mesopotamia contain similar provisions for daughters who inherit: they were often required to marry within the family to preserve the estate. Israel's provision is wider (the tribe, not just the immediate family) but participates in the same logic: inheritance preservation through controlled marriage.</p>",
"10": "<p>The daughters of Zelophehad did as YHWH commanded Moses. Five women comply with the new ruling. Their names are recalled — Mahlah, Tirzah, Hoglah, Milcah, and Noah — the same five who petitioned Moses in ch27. The narrative circle closes: the women who sought an inheritance now preserve it through their obedience. Some of these names appear as place names in the Samaria Ostraca (8th century BCE), suggesting the daughters' names were later given to towns in the Manasseh region.</p>",
"11": "<p>They married within the sons of their father's brothers — cousins within the clan of Manasseh. The text specifies 'father's brothers' children' — first-cousin marriage, which was standard and even preferred in many ancient Near Eastern cultures for exactly the land-preservation reason given here. Endogamy kept property and allegiances within defined kinship networks.</p>",
"12": "<p>Their inheritance remained in the tribe of their father's clan. The outcome vindicates the ruling and the women's obedience: the land of Zelophehad stays with Manasseh. The jubilee mechanism works as designed; the tribal allocation is intact. Five women's choices preserve a tribal inheritance across generations.</p>",
"13": "<p>'These are the commandments and the statutes which YHWH commanded by the hand of Moses to the Israelites in the plains of Moab by the Jordan opposite Jericho.' The closing formula gathers all of Numbers 28-36 under a single inscription and anchors the entire book at a specific moment: the plains of Moab, facing Jericho, on the threshold of the land. The book of Numbers ends exactly where Deuteronomy will begin — not with an arrival but with a readiness, the people at the threshold, the Torah given, the promise one step away.</p>"
}
}

comm = load_comm('mkt-context', 'numbers')
merge_comm(comm, CONTEXT)
save_comm('mkt-context', 'numbers', comm)
print('Numbers 34-36 mkt-context written.')
